{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_beargrass_ver01/data/sn86075096/00340581702/1949030101/1255.xml":{"full_text":"T r\n1\nW\nJ\nVM\ni\n\\<3*\nI\n\n\nfor Your\n\n1\nSURE YOU DO... AND\nHERE'S HOW YOU CAN OET It\nIf you arc skimming by hand using an old or inefficient\ncentrifugal separator or the water dilution method you\ncan very likely increase your cream checks by 25% or more.\nHere's how you can prove this for yourself before you buyt\n1. Just use a De Laval Separator for two weeks on a free\ntrial. We'll loan you the machine and show you how to use it.\n2. See for yourself how much bigger your cream checks\nare with a De Laval Separator. See how it would pay for\nitself in extra cream produced.\nThen if you are satisfied and like your bigger cream checks\nyou can keep the De Laval Separator and make small, easy,\nweekly payments on it in most cases the extra cream it gets\nfor you will easily make the payments.\nDo you want to make more money? Then ask your De Laval\ndealer today to arrange for your free trial.\neasy fxmm\nME TRIAL\n\nr\\\nFor lorger Herds\u2014\nDe lovai World'\u00bb\nStandard Series\u2014\n3 sizes\n\n9rv\nFor Smaller Herds\u2014\nDe Laval Junior\nSeries\u20144 sizes\n*1\nThe Dr Leva! Separator Ccmnu\nDept. 29-E\n165 Broadway. New \u00efork 4, K. I,\nPlease send me printed matter \u00abk\nfl De Lavol World's Standard\nSeries Separator\nL] Da Laval Junior Serial Separato r\nI\n1\ni\nm\nI\n1\nm\ne.\nI\nI\nI\nTHE DE LAVAL SEPARATOR COMPANY\nI\nMarne\n\ng\n165 Broadway, New York 6\n427 Randolph St., Chicago 6\n61 Beale St., San Francisco 5\nAd dw w\nIL\nairy Deportment\nDairy Income Most Stable\nBut Cost Cuts Needed to Maintain Profits\nBy GILBERT GUSLER\nMORE RUGGED economic weath\nprobably is ahead for dairymen,\nTimes are likely to be tougher than\nthe last few years and greater\neffort to reduce costs will be neces\n\u00bbary to make dairying pay. But, as\nprevious slumps, dairymen's in\ncomes probably will be more stable\nthan those of most farmers.\nHere are some important factors\nconsider in sizing up the outlook;\n1. After rising for 10 years, con\nwmers' incomes appear to be start\ning a downward trek, due to de\ncreasing employment. Because of\nrelatively fixed charges for taxes,\nrents, interest and payments on\ndebts, the housewife's grocery money\nwill shrink by a greater percentage\nthan total incomes.\npay out for dairy products has been\nclosely related to their spendable in\ncomes. During the war and post\nwar years, however, consumers spent\nless than the usual percentage of\ntheir disposable incomes for milk,\ncream, butter, and evaporated milk\nand more for cheese and ice cream.\nThe principal change was in but\nter, Whether dairy products will\nattract in the next few years the\nprewar percentage of consumer in\ncome remains to be seen.\nLower Consumption\nS. Total consumption of dairy\nproducts per person, in milk equi\nvalent is lower than in prewar years,\nbut consumption has increased in\nthose forms which bring greatest\nreturn to the producer. In whole\nmilk equivalent, domestic disappear\nance of fluid milk and cream in\ncreased 50 pounds in 1948 over 1935\n39; ice cream, 21 pounds; cheese, 15\npounds; evaporated and condensed\nmilk, 6 pounds, and dried whole\nmilk, 2 to 3 pounds. The milk equi\nvalent of butter consumed declined\nabout 136 pounds.\nMilk production per capita in 1948\nwas the lowest in several years. But,\nby using the more complete forms,\nconsumers probably obtained more\ntotal nourishment from dairy prod\nucts in 1948 than formerly. Such a\ndietary change takes place slowly\nand probably will persist, although\na partial return to butter is prob\nable as it becomes more plentiful\nand lower-priced.\n4. Competition of margarine with\nbutter will depend partly on the out\ncome of pending legislation. Butter\nconsumption probably will recover\nto some extent, but it is likely to\nbe at the expense of butter prices.\n5. Exports took 2 to 3 percent of\ntotal dairy production in the last\neight years. They probably will be\n\u00bbmaller in the next few years as\nforeign production recovers and\nMarshall plan aid shifts largely to\nindustrial goods. Imports of dairy\nproducts may increase slightly,\n6. Numbers of milk cows on farms\non June 1, 1948, were the lowest m\n17 years and 11 percent below the\npeak four years earlier. Hogs, beef\ncattle and grain farming have been\nmore attractive than dairying.\nRecent price declines on milk and\nbutter Eire again spurring sales ot\ncows. But, more young stock than\nttcual is being raised for replace\nExports Reduced\nments, so that milk cow numbers\nprobably will begin to increase this\nyear or next.\n7. Although there are fewer cows,\nthey have been culled closely and\nfed more heavily than in former\nyears. Production per cow is higher\nthan ever before,\n8. Milk production probably will\nincrease moderately in the next few\nyears. With grain prices sharply be\nlow the peak, income from other\nsources down, and milk cows cheap\ner, more farmers probably will be\ngin to milk a few cows for a regular\ncash income.\nLower Prices\n9. With lower consumer incomes\nha prospect in the next few years\nand dairy production likely to be\nPRICES RECEIVED B\u00cf FARMERS U 1*0\n\u00bbAR ASD POSTWAR PERIODS\nf\u00abr\nHUE\n.<49\n\u25a0u.n\n\n\nwc\n\\T7 C\n7\nt\n\nf\n1.25\nJm. *49\u2014\n\u26660.60\ns\n7\n.to\n*35 *37 *39 *41 *43 *45 *47 *49 *51\n\u2022M *12 *i\u00ab *16 *18 *20 *28 *94 \"26\n-1935-49\n-1910-26\n3\u00bb ta fro\u00ab D.S. Department ot Amenltare\nIn spile of government efforts jo pre\nvent inflation and deflation, prices up\nto now have behaved much the same\nas in the previous World war period,\nallowing for the greater length of the\nlast war and the greater strength of\ninflationary forces. In World war 1,\ndairy prices to farmers more than dou\nbled. After the 1920-21 break, they\nstabilized for several years about 50\nto 60 percent over prewar. In World\nwar 2. prices nearly trebled. If a de\nflationary trend has begun, prices\nmight again lose about half of the rise\nbefore they stabilize.\n\nmoderately higher, prices probably\nwill average considerably lower than\nin the past year or two. Prices tor\nfluid milk probably will be much\nmore profitable than for manufac\nturing pi i l k.\n10. Distribution charges will tend\nto stay high. Much of the price ad\njustment because of the housewife's\nsmaller budget is likely to be im\nposed on the producer. Profits of\ndairy companies per unit of product\ndo not appear high, but wages and\nsalaries, which make up a large\nshare of distribution costs, have\nbeen increased materially. Union\nwage rates are likely to remain rela\ntively high even in a recession or\ndepression.\nDuring the inflationary price rise,\ntoe farmer's share of the consumer's\ndollar spent for dairy products in\ncreased from about 50 cents in 1935\n39 to more than 60 cents. It prob\nably will decline toward the prewar\nlevel in the next few years,\n11. Feeds will be abundant and\nstocks of grain are likely to pile vtp.","height":"15906","width":"11271"}}
